* This file contains in-plane transport parameters at 300 K for silicon
* under biaxial tensile strain present when a thin silicon film is grown
* on top of a relaxed SiliconGermanium substrate (in-plane refers to 
* charge transport parallel to the interface to SiliconGermanium as is 
* the case in MOSFETs).
* 
* In the physics section of the Dessis command file, the Germanium
* content of the SiliconGermanium substrate at the interface to the
* StrainedSilicon channel has to be specified (this value determines
* the strain) according to
*
*   MoleFraction  (RegionName=["Region.6"]
*          XFraction = 0.2 Grading = 0.0 ) 
*
* where the material of Region.6 is StrainedSilicon.
*
* Band offsets and bulk mobility data are obtained from the model-solid
* theory of Van de Walle and Monte Carlo simulations as described in
* F. M. Bufler and W. Fichtner, Applied Physics Letters, vol. 81, No. 1,
* pp. 82-84 (2002).
* 
* The present values for the parameters B, C and delta of the 
* Darwish-type surface mobility model (THE PhuMob MODEL HAS TO BE
* ACTIVATED in the DESSIS command file when using this parameter file!)
* were extracted
* in a MOS diode at a high effective field (where the Si control
* measurements of the references below were in good agreement with
* the universal mobility curve of Si and where the neglected effect
* of the SiGe substrate is minimal) of around 0.7 MV/cm to reproduce 
* the experimental data reported in
* M. T. Currie et al., Journal of Vacuum Science & Technology B, 
* vol. 19, no. 6, pp.2268-2279 (2001);
* C. W. Leitz et al., Journal of Applied Physics, vol. 92, no. 7,
* pp. 3745-3751 (2002).
*
* At present, the QuantumPotentialParameters cannot be parametrizied
* as a function of strain; the values specified correspond to XFraction = 0.2.
*
* See also the parameter file StrainedSi_SiGe.par for a consistent set
* of parameters for the material system described in the first paragraph.

Auger * coefficients:
{ * R_Auger = ( C_n n + C_p p ) ( n p - ni_eff^2)
  * with C_n,p = (A + B (T/T0) + C (T/T0)^2) (1 + H exp(-{n,p}/N0))
	A	= 6.7000e-32 ,	7.2000e-32	# [cm^6/s]
	B	= 2.4500e-31 ,	4.5000e-33	# [cm^6/s]
	C	= -2.2000e-32 ,	2.6300e-32	# [cm^6/s]
	H	= 3.46667 ,	8.25688	# [1]
	N0	= 1.0000e+18 ,	1.0000e+18	# [cm^(-3)]
}


Scharfetter * relation and trap level for SRH recombination:
{ * tau = taumin + ( taumax - taumin ) / ( 1 + ( N/Nref )^gamma)
  * tau(T) = tau * ( (T/300)^Talpha )          (TempDep)
  * tau(T) = tau * exp( Tcoeff * ((T/300)-1) ) (ExpTempDep)
	taumin	= 0.0000e+00 ,	0.0000e+00	# [s]
	taumax	= 1.0000e-05 ,	3.0000e-06	# [s]
	Nref	= 1.0000e+16 ,	1.0000e+16	# [cm^(-3)]
	gamma	= 1 ,	1	# [1]
	Talpha	= -1.5000e+00 ,	-1.5000e+00	# [1]
	Tcoeff	= 2.55 ,	2.55	# [1]
	Etrap	= 0.0000e+00	# [eV]
}

Epsilon
{ *  Ratio of the permittivities of material and vacuum

  * epsilon() = epsilon
  * Mole fraction dependent model.
  * If only constant parameters are specified, those values will be
  * used for any mole fraction instead of the interpolation below.
  * Linear interpolation is used on the interval [0,1].
	epsilon	= 11.7	# [1]
}

*  refractiveindex{...}
*  By default, for mole fraction dependency of parameters
*  of the model, the following linear interpolation is applied
*  between two materials: P = x * P(Silicon) + (1-x) * P(Silicon)
*  where P(m) is a parameter of material m.
*  If the parameters are specified, then its values
*  will be used instead of the interpolation.


*  LatticeHeatCapacity{...}
*  By default, for mole fraction dependency of parameters
*  of the model, the following linear interpolation is applied
*  between two materials: P = x * P(Silicon) + (1-x) * P(Silicon)
*  where P(m) is a parameter of material m.
*  If the parameters are specified, then its values
*  will be used instead of the interpolation.


*  Kappa{...}
*  By default, for mole fraction dependency of parameters
*  of the model, the following linear interpolation is applied
*  between two materials: P = x * P(Silicon) + (1-x) * P(Silicon)
*  where P(m) is a parameter of material m.
*  If the parameters are specified, then its values
*  will be used instead of the interpolation.


